12 PART II. REGULATORY CHANGES
13 SECTION 2. G.S. 110-86(5a) reads as rewritten:
14 "(5a) Lead teacher. – An individual who is responsible for planning and
15 implementing the daily program of activities for a group no more than two
16 groups of children in a child care facility."
17 SECTION 3. G.S. 110-90(4) reads as rewritten:
18 "(4) To issue a rated license to any child care facility which meets the standards
19 established by this Article as follows:
20 a. For any child care facility currently holding a license of two to five
21 stars or any new license issued to a child care facility with a rating of
22 two to five stars, the rating shall be based on (i) program standards and
23 (ii) education levels of staff. When evaluating program standards, the
24 Department shall consider the facility's staff/child ratios, space
25 requirements, continuous quality improvement standards, family and
26 community engagement practices, environmental rating scale
27 evaluations, curriculum, child observation and assessment, staff
28 coaching or mentoring, or accreditation by a national or regional
29 accrediting agency with early childhood standards. When evaluating
30 education levels of staff, the Department shall consider any early
31 childhood and child development coursework, early childhood
32 education certificates, Child Development Associate credentials,
33 associate or bachelor's degrees, continuous quality improvement
34 standards for staff, continuing education units, early childhood
35 education competency evaluations, work experience in child care,
36 including staff granted the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential
37 based on experience pursuant to G.S. 110-91, coaching or mentoring
38 completed, and education standards within an accreditation award.
39 …."
40 SECTION 4. G.S. 110-91(6) reads as rewritten:
41 "(6) Space and Equipment Requirements. – There shall be no less than 25 square
42 feet of indoor space for each child for which a child care center is licensed,
43 exclusive of closets, passageways, kitchens, and bathrooms, and this floor
44 space shall provide during rest periods 200 cubic feet of airspace per child for
45 which the center is licensed. There shall be adequate outdoor play area for
46 each child under rules adopted by the Commission which shall be related to
47 the size of center and the availability and location of outside land area. In no
48 event shall the minimum required exceed 75 square feet per child. The outdoor
49 area shall be protected to assure the safety of the children receiving child care
50 by an adequate fence or other protection. A center operated in a public school
51 shall be deemed to have adequate fencing protection. A center operating
