24 SECTION 7. G.S. 110-91(8) reads as rewritten:
25 "(8) Qualifications for Staff. – Qualifications for child care staff are as follows:
26 a. All child care center administrators shall be at least 21 years of age.
27 All child care center administrators shall have the North Carolina
28 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent as
29 determined by the Department. All child care administrators
30 performing administrative duties as of the date this act becomes law
31 and child care administrators who assume administrative duties at any
32 time after this act becomes law and until September 1, 1998, shall
33 obtain the required credential by September 1, 2000. Child care
34 administrators who assume administrative duties after September 1,
35 1998, shall begin working toward the completion of the North Carolina
36 Early Childhood Administration Credential or its equivalent within six
37 months after assuming administrative duties and shall complete the
38 credential or its equivalent within two years after beginning work to
39 complete the credential. Each child care center shall be under the
40 direction or supervision of a person meeting these requirements. All
41 staff counted toward meeting the required staff-child ratio shall be at
42 least 16 years of age, provided that persons younger than 18 years of
43 age work under the direct supervision of a credentialed staff person
44 who is at least 21 years of age.
45 b. All lead teachers in a child care center shall have at least a North
46 Carolina Early Childhood Credential or its equivalent as determined
47 by the Department. Lead teachers shall either (i) be enrolled in the
48 North Carolina Early Childhood Credential coursework or its
49 equivalent as determined by the Department within six months after
50 becoming employed as a lead teacher or within six months after this
51 act becomes law, whichever is later, and shall complete the credential
