General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (Division), shall, for courses offered by a community college in the North Carolina Community
2 Colleges System (NCCCS), assign credit for continuing education courses on the same basis as
3 curriculum courses designated by NCCCS as equivalent to the continuing education courses for
4 the purpose of providing any credential offered by the Division.
5 SECTION 11. The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
6 Development and Early Education, shall:
7 (1) Not later than December 1, 2025, and in consultation with the North Carolina
8 Community Colleges System, create a North Carolina School
9 Age/Out-of-School Care Credential that aligns with a new curriculum course
10 and continuing education course entitled "Introduction to School Age Care
11 and Education."
12 (2) Award the North Carolina Early Childhood Administration Credential or the
13 North Carolina Family Child Care Credential to individuals who have
14 successfully completed continuing education courses that are equivalent to
15 child care curriculum courses, as determined by the Community Colleges
16 System. The Community Colleges System shall ensure that the continuing
17 education courses are comparable to the corresponding curriculum courses in
18 course descriptions, competencies, and hour requirements and shall state the
19 credential that is to be awarded for each continuing education course.
20 SECTION 12.(a) The Commissioner of the Department of Insurance shall establish
21 a workgroup to examine the potential for developing group liability insurance plan opportunities
22 for all child care providers. The workgroup shall consist of representatives from all of the
23 following:
24 (1) The Department of Insurance.
25 (2) The insurance industry.
26 (3) The child care industry, including foster family homes and out-of-school
27 providers.
28 (4) The Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
29 Development and Early Education.
30 (5) The American Tort Reform Association.
31 SECTION 12.(b) The workgroup shall develop findings and recommendations
32 related to at least the following:
33 (1) Potential methods for creating group liability insurance plan opportunities for
34 all child care providers.
35 (2) Reforms that could reduce group liability insurance plan premiums.
36 (3) Tort reforms that could reduce the liability damages of child care providers.
37 SECTION 12.(c) By January 1, 2026, the Department of Insurance shall report the
38 findings and recommendations of the workgroup to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee
39 on Health and Human Services, the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on General
40 Government, and the Fiscal Research Division.
41
42 PART III. EFFECTIVE DATE
43 SECTION 13. This act is effective when it becomes law.
